Custom Directive.
    - Creating our own directive based on application requirement called as Custom Directive.

    - In AngularJS We Can Use Custom Directives in 3 ways.

        1.Element
        2.Attribute
        3.CSS Class

    Ex.
        my_directive

       <my_directive></my_directive>  // using like Element

       <div my_directive></div>      // Attribute

       <div class="my_directive"></div> //CSS Class

Properties Of Custom Directives.

1. restrict.

Ex.

    restrict : "E" // Element Level Usage

    restrict : "A"  // Attribute Level Usage

    restrict : "C"  // CSS Class Level Usage

    restrict:"ECA"


2. template

    used to add the inline html to the custom directive.

Ex.

     app.directive("attrType",attrType);

     function attrType(){
            return{
                    restrict : "A",
                    template : "<b>Welcome to Custom Directive</b>"
            }
     }

     <div attr-type></div> //Welcome to Custom Directive



3.templateUrl.

    used to add the external templates to the custom directives.

---------------
templates
    sample.html
---------------

sample.html
-
<h1>Welcome to Custom Directives !</h1>


---------------
directives
    my_directive.js
---------------

app.directive("my_directive",my_directive);
function my_directive(){
    return{
        restrict:'C',
        templateUrl:"templates/sample.html"
    }
}


<div class="my_directive"></div> //Welcome to Custom Directives !


4.controller

    - used to define the controller to the template of a custom directive.

-----------------
templates
    sample.html
----------------

{{var_one}}


-------------------
controller
    sample.js
-------------------

app.controller("sample",sample);
sample.$inject=["$scope"];
function sample($scope){
    $scope.var_one = "I am from custom directive";
}


----------------------
directives
    my_directive.js
----------------------

app.directive("my_directive",my_directive);

function my_directive(){
    return{
        restrict:'E',
        templateUrl:'templates/sample.html',
        controller:'sample'
    }
}

<my_directive></my_directive> //I am from custom directive












